3 must-do exercises to grow your glutes ⬇️

▫️Bulgarian Split Squats 
(The split squat as a unilateral exercise, can produce a more pinpointed approach to glute development and hamstrings when compared to a back/front squat)

▫️Deadlift 
(All deadlifts are great for your glutes. But variations like the Romanian, sumo, deficit, and single-leg deadlift are some of the best options. This is due to their higher muscle recruitment and range of motion)

▫️Hip Thrust 
(Without a question hip thrusts are one of the most effective ways to add size and strength to your glutes.
Highly recommend reading a book Glute Lab by @bretcontreras1 )

⭐️ I usually add some isolated exercises at the end of the workout like kickbacks or weighted donkey kicks.
⭐️ And don’t forget about the warm up! I like to do a lil glute activation before the workout (banded squats, lateral walk, single leg glute bridges, etc to “wake up” the glutes)

Hip Thrust Do’s✅ & Don’ts ❌:

❌ Limited range of motion - Not going all the way to the top where the highest engagement of the glutes happens
✅ Full range of motion - The hip thrust is all about engaging and activating the glutes, so it’s important to squeeze them hard at the top of the movement to fully engage the muscle fibres. Pause and hold the top position for a second or two before lowering your hips. However, make sure to don’t overextend your hips at the top of the movement, as this can lead to strain in your lower back.

❌ Arching the lower back 
✅ Engage your core muscles to maintain stability and prevent arching in your lower back

❌ Neck is not in line with the spine (head is resting on the bench or you’re looking up)
✅  Maintain a neutral spine - Keep your chin tucked in and your neck neutral throughout the movement.

+ ✅ Maintain a 90’ angle in the knees and drive through your heels as you lift your hips up, rather than pushing off your toes.

Motivation is what gets you started. Habit is what keeps you going! 📈 It’s all about consistency!

Sometimes, no matter how important your goals are to you, it’s a struggle to bring your best effort to your workout (or work up the motivation to make it happen at all). But whether you’re trying to lose weight, train for a race, build some muscle, keep your stress in check, or any of the other worthwhile reasons to make fitness a part of your life, staying consistent is key, even when you really, really, really don’t feel like it.

5 MUST DO GLUTE EXERCISES 🍑

1️⃣ SQUATS - The OG of lower body workouts. Squats engage your entire lower body, emphasizing the glutes when performed correctly. Mix it up with Bulgarian split squats, back squats and sumo squats to target different angles and muscles. 

2️⃣ HIP THRUSTS - This queen of glute exercises activates your gluteus Maximus, giving you that round, lifted look. Pro tip: try single-leg hip thrusts for an extra burn 🔥

3️⃣ REVERSE LUNGES - these fire up your glutes and improve hip stability. Slightly lean forward to mainly target the glutes and not the quads and main sure the majority of weight is in the front leg, pressing the heal into the floor.

4️⃣ KICKBACKS - Sculpt and lift with precision! Target the gluteus medius and minimus. 💡Tip: Control the movement to maximize muscle engagement and minimize momentum. Experiment with different food positions (neutral, turned out) to target various parts of your flutes.

5️⃣ GOOD MORNINGS - Hinge for results. Good mornings work your lower back/upper glutes (for that beautiful round and lifted look) as well as the hamstrings. Another great hinge variation would be the deadlifts! 

Consistency is key! 🔑 Incorporate these moves into your routine and watch those glutes growing!!
